<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom" xmlns:media="http://search.yahoo.com/mrss/" xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/"><channel><title>NYT &gt; Technology</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/section/technology</link><description>Technology industry news, commentary, and analysis, with reporting on big tech, startups, and internet culture. The New York Times is a hub for conversation about news and ideas.</description><atom:link rel="self" href="https://rss.nytimes.com/services/xml/rss/nyt/Technology.xml" type="application/rss+xml" /><item><title>How to Remove Apps You Never Use (or at Least Hide Them)</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/10/technology/personaltech/iphone-android-app-removal.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</link><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/10/technology/personaltech/iphone-android-app-removal.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</guid><atom:link rel="standout" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/10/technology/personaltech/iphone-android-app-removal.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss" /><description>If you need space back on your phone or tablet, removing built-in and unused apps can help free up storage and reduce screen clutter.</description><dc:creator>J. D. Biersdorfer</dc:creator><pubDate>Wed, 10 Jun 2026 09:02:01 GMT</pubDate><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Smartphone</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Tablet computer</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">None</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Android</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Apple</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Google</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Samsung</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Mobile Apps</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Computers and the Internet</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Tech Industry</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Service Content</category><media:content url="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2026/06/10/technology/personaltech/10BIZ-TECHTIP-TOP/10BIZ-TECHTIP-TOP-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600.jpg" medium="image"><media:credit>Apple</media:credit><media:description>In the Storage settings, Apple’s iOS software for iPad and iPhone shows how much of the device’s storage is being used and offers several ways to reclaim space.</media:description></media:content></item><item><title>Should You Outsource Your Morning Routine to a Chatbot?</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/04/magazine/ai-chatbot-morning-routine-videos.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</link><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/04/magazine/ai-chatbot-morning-routine-videos.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</guid><atom:link rel="standout" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/04/magazine/ai-chatbot-morning-routine-videos.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss" /><description>A.I. wants to help you start the day. Its suggestions? Drink coffee and get dressed.</description><dc:creator>Sophie Haigney</dc:creator><pubDate>Thu, 04 Jun 2026 09:03:39 GMT</pubDate><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Artificial intelligence</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Habits and Routines</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Social Media</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Anthropic</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">OpenAI</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">TikTok</category><media:content url="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2026/06/14/magazine/14mag-screenland/14mag-screenland-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600.jpg" medium="image"><media:credit>Aniyah Uniquee/@Aniyahuniquee</media:credit></media:content></item><item><title>Meta Has Created a Prediction Markets App</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/23/technology/meta-prediction-markets-app.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</link><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/23/technology/meta-prediction-markets-app.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</guid><atom:link rel="standout" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/23/technology/meta-prediction-markets-app.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss" /><description>The experimental app, internally called “Arena,” would be independent of Facebook and Instagram. It could compete for attention with Polymarket and Kalshi, the biggest prediction markets.</description><dc:creator>Mike Isaac and David Yaffe-Bellany</dc:creator><pubDate>Tue, 23 Jun 2026 16:40:17 GMT</pubDate><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Meta</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Prediction Markets</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Mobile Apps</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Social Media</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Computers and the Internet</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Tech Industry</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Mark E Zuckerberg</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Kalshi</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Polymarket</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">internal-open-access-from-nl</category><media:content url="https://static01.nyt.com/image